related_items.title: [Turk leaving Lausanne Conference with Constantinople and membership in the League of Nations]
description: 1 drawing. | Cartoon shows an exuberant Turkish man with a laurel wreath around his head, bounding down the stairs from a door labeled "Lausanne Conference."  He carries a model of a city labeled "Constantinople" in one hand and a scroll reading "Membership in League of Nations" under his arm.  After the First World War, the Ottoman Empire (which had sided with the Germans) was broken up and put under the protection of various European states. Turkish nationalists fought to establish an independent Turkey, which was finally granted at the Lausanne Conference in 1923. In addition to independence, Turkey also acquired undisputed ownership of Constantinople (Istanbul).
